@Article(Franklin92,
  title="Register Traffic Analysis for Streamlining Inter-Operation
     Communication in Fine-Grain Parallel Processors",
  author="M. Franklin and  G. S. Sohi",
  journal="SIGMICRO Newsletter",
  pages="236-245",
  month=dec, year=1992, volume=23,
  key="This paper analyzes the register file traffic in a load/store
   architecture with a view to motivate the development of alternate
   inter-operation communication mechanism that reduce the bandwidth
   demanded of a centralized register file.  We first provide metrics to
   characterize the register traffic.  These metrics deal with the degree
   and locality of use of the register instances created. We then present
   the results of a simulation study that uses the MIPS R2000 architecture
   and the SPEC benchmark programs.  We have two major results. First, a
   large number of the register instances are used only once, and the
   average degree of use of register instances is about 2. Second, most of
   the register instances are used up soon after they are created (within
   30-40 instructions). This suggests that alternate inter-operation
   communication mechanisms that exploit the temporal locality of use of
   register instances are likely to be effective in reducing the traffic
   burden on the centralized register file. The second result was pivotal
   in the design of the distributed register file for the multiscalar
   processing paradigm.")

